column28: Notes
strong winds at mid and low elevations too
Seems like 12/25 didnt need to have wind slabs as p1
12/26 BTL should have been MOD if rain forecast verified. Turns out LOW worked because I blew the rain fx too.
deep slab as additional concern for today's Fx
today may be low at all elevations if we end up on the low end of the fx storm totals
Depending on winds it may be low at treeline elevations
Winds were highly variable across fx zone, areas that saw high winds have potenital for lingering wind slabs today
Storm delivered, large natural activity 1/13-1/14, big Aly results
Wind showed up earlier than wx fx was predicting
Moist snow down low was not as reactive as anticipated on wind rolls BTL
Winds started actively transporting snow at upper treeline elevations midday
Not sure if the storm totals will add up today. Could be mod at treeline if less snow than forecast
1/27 may have been MOD at treeline. Seemed that way at Tincan, low snow totals and little wind. Storm snow sluffing. Maybe CON in Girdwood/Placer?
crust up to 1000'
Uncertain about whether winds will make it down to treeline elevation band
Interested to know whether the winds reached treeline and it was actually considerable in some treeline locations
2/10 wind fx verified. widespread wind effect at treeline. Natural activity in alpine
Surprised to hear about naturals along hwy today...
Was torn on whether to go moderate at treeline because of incoming storm in afternoon/evening
Might be storm slab if precip starts earlier than expected (3pm)
2/14 interface not as reactive as we thought it might be. Mixed results in pits from obs for the day, no more activity
Storm is under-delivering precip, over delivering wind
Persisent Slab going to unlikely?
On the fence w/ TL danger level this morning. Went CON since Squirrel/Skookum are touchy. Same issue w/ storm slab vs wind slab for p1
Took deep slab out. Not enough load to make this a concern, seems human tr. is very unlikely
Stuck with storm slab as p1 after looking at NAC guidelines
Winds got up to 15-20 mph with gusts to 30 mph from 11am to 11pm
Increasing winds tomorrow leading to development of fresh, touchy wind slabs in alpine
Outflow NW wind event expected to peak Saturday/tomorrow

Decided in the morning to set danger at Treeline to moderate due to lower winds than expected at all T Pass weather stations. Had planned on considerable based on discussion with Wendy the night before
Not quite sure how the 11/25-26 wind slabs are healing. Facets/SH below?
Was a conservative move to make TL moderate 12/1/22. I think this will be true only in areas seeing strong winds (crow pass, seattle ridge, corner of 4940 etc)
No reassessment due to no field day 12.1.22
Inteniontally kept it at moderate in alpine due to saturday fx and clear weather. Planning to move to low on Sunday
Not quite sure if there will be enough wind to make for MOD in the alpine today...
On the fence for reassessing the alpine. Hard saying without any field info, but the wind stayed lighter than I thought it would.
Dependent upon new snow amounts and outlfow wind strength

Decided to keep treeline considerable today for travel advice and because adjacent areas to our forecast zone have dangerous snowpack conditions but no forecast. Easy to imagine wind slabs at treeline in many location within the forecast zone but did not find them at TPass yesterday due to that are being sheltered from NW winds.
Looks like ~6"+ of snow during daylight hours tomorrow, likely to go to high overnight on Sunday into Monday.
Storm didn't start picking up until right before sunset, maybe didn't hit high until after dark

On the fence about storm slab as P1 today since we got 0.7" SWE in Girdwood (Alyeska). Considerable may be an over forecast, especially for treeline, but we have a lot of uncertianty right now and combination of higher snowfall totals and wind today in parts of Fx regions justified conservative ratings.
Stabilizing wind slabs, wondering about Gwood crust issue Aly is seeing
Whumphing and lots of avalanche activity in Crow Creek area. Obs of whumphing in T Pass as well.
Lots of tracks, little signs of instability, poor strurcture - scary MOD, no human tr avalanches on this layer yet
Looking like status quo for the time
Active wind loading and natural avalacnhes near Alyeska. Isolated area with high winds. Probably considerable danger in areas with those winds though
Lack of info kept the 27th HIGH danger even though it was prob Cons.
With stout MF crust up to 2200'+ the liklihood of avalanches in treeline seemed pretty low. Persistent WL and wind/storm slabs in alpine seem most likely
Timing of storm incoming tomorrow will determine when the danger increases. Could go to high on Sunday early AM if storm arrives early.

Felt like low danger at treeine in crow creek yesterday. Lots of moist snow in the snowpack. Still able to penetrate to the ground with a boot, but skis were supportable on top of the Christmas crust. We only made it to 2000' so it is hard to say what it was doingn at the upper treeline band, but I assume it was still wet snow on the surface there.
Prob gonna be Mod Jan 5 but maybe Cons for travel advise

At least in the area we travelled on Jan 4 wind slabs were not reactive at treeline and the new snow was not reative as storm slabs. Maybe in deeper new snow areas it was Cons, but not what we saw in the field
Low confidence in wx forecast based on NWS discussions
Low confidence in wx forecast based on NWS discussions
All about travel advise... possible scary large avalanches all aspects
Increasing winds and light snowfall will bump danger back up in the alpine. Unsure about P1 and P2 tomorrow. Deep slabs more consequences but much less likely that wind slabs with SH underneath.
Lots of uncertianty in weather models. Depending on new snow amounts today and tomorrow the danger could stay moderate in TL band.
Danger was probably at high overnight. Natural in Kern hit the tracks, train got plugged into debris.

Going to high danger today felt kind of borderline. I'm not confident weather stations were reporting accurate snowfall totals and the strong winds overnight pushed me over the treshold. I think D2 human triggered are very likely, so that was the deciding factor. Upper end of treeline might be similar conditions to alpine, except much lower probability of avalanches stepping down to Thanksgiving crust/facet layer so max size is smaller for treeline.

Given sensitivity on 1/18 I think it was a good call to go High in the alpine with active weather loading what is clearly an unstable snowpack. Didn't get in the field so hard to be certain but it seems like the right forecast for the day.
Tomorrow will have very strong winds and moderate snowfall, which should make natural likely and human triggerd very likely on BSH.
I think liklihood of triggering is trending toward possible, but based on travel advice I'm guessing danger will stay CONS in alpine tomorrow. Also deep persistent problem trending toward unlikely.
Sun triggered dry loose which triggered some shallow soft slabs
Headed towards low?? Need more obs
New snow amounts uncertain
Not much field info from 2/5 so hard to say. Water totals were light at Center ridge, but reports saying 18" new snow with strong winds probably hit high.
Stabilizing storm snow
Outflow winds....
Alpine might have been pushing considerable. Hard saying without any obs from up high.
Storm snow not that much and stabilizing
Did not get into real wind slab terrain yesterday, but it might have been closer to moderate in the alpine.
status quo with questional buried layers... how weak are they really?
Low confidence in reassessment because I haven't been in the field
less precip than forecast, also slightly less winds. Didn't feel considerable at treeline, no info from Alpine but that may have been moderate too.
Depending on winds could drop to mod tomorrow in alpine
Lots of uncertainly for snow totals - also very light snow 5%?
Again, undertainly for how much snow fell - maybe it's more Mod ? NW winds uncertain too
Winds were light in TPass, which lead me to decrease the TL danger just due to conditions in our high use areas. Certainly along Turnagain Arm the danger may have been CONS in TL.
Really felt like i was guessing at how the snow would react to warming. Very low fx confidence today/
Uncertain on how much wind transport is possible, but gusts up to 40 mph seemed to high for low danger in alpine.
New snow amounts uncertain - winds enough for wind slabs if even snow falls
Possible SAB for saturday with breif calm period between two strong storm pulses.
Issed avalanche warning from 6a Sat to 6a Sun
cooling and little precip? Sun in the big ? and what it could activate
P2 headed towards deep slab
Unsure about when storm will finish up...

Was very close to making treeline elevation band considerable today. My hesitation was based on Wendy's concern about very large avalanches on south facing slopes like repeat offender. This was an intentionally conservative forecast based on uncertainty and lack in recent info plus lots of loading over the past week.
Daytime warming/sun more than fx which triggered wet loose and some slabs
Will sunshine trigger natural slabs today?
Not quite sure about BTL, but seems like a good idea to stick with CON because of long runouts
Going to be hard to drop to moderate with this setup
Will sun and warm temps reactivate deep slab?
Wind didn't do too much, any warming issues in low elevations?
cursts didn't really soften too much to cause issues
Wet loose did not really develop due to cloud cover yesterday. Springtim MF crust at lower elevations feels more like low danger.
Unsure snow amounts....
Sun and afternoon heating is the quesion...
A little bit of snow and wind bumped up danger in alpine today, but moderate in apline would have probably been more accurate for most of the Fx zone
Hard saying how the snowpack will react to continued light rain
Continuing wet and warm stormy weather pattern
Not sure about timing of incoming storm. Could be mod, mod, mod during the day on Tuesday

Want to discuss w forecast team whether keeping at mod due to glides is okay. Glide activity seems especially widespread and active right now, so low danger seems like a misnomer when very large avalnaches are spontaneously releasing.
2-3" thin skier tr. wind slabs on Tincan
Winds didn't pick up until sunset
3 problems today with persistent, wind, and glide. High uncertainty with persistent.
Looks like winds are going to pick back up tomorrow
Not confident in outlook danger ratings
Lots of uncertainty about lower elevation slopes (<1000') that got wet snow and rain yesterday.
Struggling with BTL elevation danger rating. Low?
storm supposed to put 1-1.5 qpf overnight tonight
storm did not produce, 4-8" or so is all
Maybe going to Low at all elevations?
Not sure if there will be enough weather tomorrow to bring alpine back to MOD
Didn't think avalanches would be big enough to go CON in alpine
Wind and snow did not pick up during the day, at least in during our field day in Girdwood - mostly happened overnight
Maybe could have been CON at treeline. Fair bit of new snow avalanche activity, but all reported in the alpine that I know of
Outlook fx very uncertian due to snowfall totals changing a lot in weather model runs
Surface crust up to 1800' on all but most northerly aspects
Kept snowing in Placer/Turnagain another foot, felt like high all elevations for 3/13
Tough fx for 3/30. Wildy different precip totals from Girdwood/Placer to Turnagain. Seems like the only places seeing traffic did not get enough snow to go to high.
Considerable seems to high, however it was challenging to speak to the storm increasing intensity through the danger rating.
Post storm, it was difficult to match danger and travel advice.
Not sure what next storm will bring for wind and precip
For outlook- could go to deep slab tomorrow?
Increase to high in the afternoon if weather verifies
The new snow seemed to stabilize really quickly, there weren't very many people out, but there was no avalanche activity post storm that we are aware of
The trend is that we did not recieve as much precip and warm temps overnight so my bet is that the storm was overforecast. I got a bet with Andrew so we will wait and see.
should stabilize quickly, maybe mod tomorrow...
Wendy, Andrew, and John reported low danger conditions in the mid elevations on 1.28
If the wind forecast increases tomorrow may be mod in the alpine for wind slab
We'll see what happens with the winds today
Winds began to die as the forecast was being published. Lets see how the day goes.
Wind may not show up but WS over weak layers added to moderate decision
Depends on snowfall and wind, first wave of storm underpeformed on snowfall
Wind and snow didn't show up as forecast yesterday. Buried SH in mid elevations and Moderow's ob pushed me to mod at treeline today
winds are forecast to increase tomorrow
Another report of rider caught and carried yesterday, conditions are still touchy
Snowboarder caught and carried 300' on BSH 1-2' deep
Depends on SWE totals
2nd day posting Special avalanche Bulletin
Probably could drop wind slab
I think we are trending to moderate, but wanted group consensus
We are probably trending moderate, but are hesitant to drop because of the fatal avalanche one week ago and because of the people that only look at the color
In hindsight and after getting reports there were numerous new glide avalanches yesterday, also today may not be as dangerous if clouds come in early.
No forecast yesterday with spring schedule. Maybe 1 deep slab on Pyramid
